As a reminder, our virtual wellness programming events begin tonight, and parent/guardian(s) of students in all grade levels are encouraged to attend!

TONIGHT! Tuesday August 25th: 7-8:30pm:
Lisa Athan, the Founder and Executive Director of Grief Speaks, will be holding an informational session for parent/guardian(s) prior to the return to school. In her session, Lisa will introduce strategies to support the emotional needs of children and how to manage the various stressors impacting parents and families today. There will also be time devoted to your questions and processing.

Please follow this link to join the virtual event. https://meet.google.com/xpp-sjde-wjh

The event begins at 7:00pm tonight. When you follow the above link, you will be prompted to request to be admitted to the event. Attendees will be admitted beginning at 6:55pm through 7:15pm. After 7:15pm, admission will be closed.

Visit our Wellness Programs Page for more information on upcoming events and services.

At the July 27th Board of Education meeting, the Board voted to amend the 2020-2021 school year calendar. Staff will report to the district on Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday, September 1, 2, and 3 for Professional Learning regarding the hybrid instruction model that we plan to implement this fall due to COVID-19. Details on these staff days will be forthcoming. Details on the hybrid plan for reopening will be shared with parents, staff and the community by August 4th.

The first day of school for students will now be Tuesday, September 8th.

post_text:
8th Grade Yearbook Information

For those who were unable to pick up 8th grade yearbooks last week, a new pick up date is available.

We have organized a second curbside pick up that will follow the Governor’s Executive Order, and limit in-person contact.

Two pick up times will be available to choose from on Thursday, July 30.

Afternoon
3:00-4:00 pm

Evening
6:00-7:00 pm

DIRECTIONS:
Please wear a mask at all times and maintain social distancing of 6 feet.
Please use the entrance on Hillside Crescent.
Please have a sign with your child’s last name in your window. Follow the driveway to exit on Franklin Avenue.
If you feel sick, please do not come to your scheduled pick up time. We will make arrangements to get your yearbook to you at a later date.
If you are unable to pick up your yearbook during either of these times, please reach out to the middle school vice principal, Mr. Sullivan, at msullivan@nutleyschools.org to arrange an alternate date.

If you would like to purchase a yearbook and have not yet done so, please email JHWMSyearbook@nutleyschools.org for details.

This Friday, June 5th, is our elementary schools’ first ever “Virtual Field Day”!

1. Inside your Schoology Course, click on the “Physical Education” folder, where you will find a Virtual Field Day message that includes a “Flipgrid Code.” Copy or write down that code, as you will need it for Step 3.

3. Click on “Enter a Flip Code” in the top left-hand corner and enter the “Flip Code” your Phys. Ed. teacher shared with you.

post_text:
We have no words, no card, cute picture, poem, meme or video that could capture what the Nutley staff brings to the district, provides to the students, and adds to the community.

We did think this song was beautiful:
https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=ighFo0i0nrA

Thank you to all of our amazing faculty, staff and administrators everyday, but especially today, for all of your incredible work during the craziest year we have ever had. You are truly champions! There was never any doubt that our staff could rise to any occasion no matter how unusual or unpredictable, but it is so special to see you work and thrive under such unprecedented conditions. Our students are so lucky to have you as their teachers, support staff, nurses, administrators; and we are so fortunate to have you as our colleagues. Thank you for your dedication, compassion, knowledge, flexibility, caring, humor, teamwork, expertise and hard work.

We miss you and will look forward to telling you in person how grateful we are to you for always making Nutley so proud. #NutleyStrongerTogether!

post_text: Governor Murphy announces school closures through the remainder of this school year. "This is a difficult decision and I know that many students, parents, and staff would like to be able to return to school," Murphy said in a press release. "However, I have been unwavering on the message that we need to make decisions based on science, not emotion. And while New Jersey is making great strides in mitigating the spread of COVID-19, science tells us that at this point, we can't safely re-open our schools."

John H. Walker Middle School's Drama Club was set to open their first ever junior level, professional musical, Into the Woods, Jr., this weekend, with performances set for tonight (Thursday 4/30), tomorrow (Friday 5/1), and Saturday (5/2).

A few of Mrs. Mcdonnell's Digital Production students spent some time over the weekend interviewing some of Ms. Alamo's Drama Club students and put a segment together to honor those students and their time spent rehearsing from December - March. Please enjoy this video filled with memories, reflections, singing and even some bloopers at the end!

post_text:
According to Governor Phil Murphy, all New Jersey schools will remained closed until, at least, May 15. He announced this at Thursday's press conference.

"I'm announcing that our public schools will remain closed through at least Friday, May 15, another four weeks. I made this decision in careful consultation with Judy and the Department of Health, as well as Dr. Repollet at the Department of Education, among other key stakeholders. Let me be perfectly clear. There's nobody who wants to open the schools more than I do. I'm a father of four kids, one of whom is in high school, and I want him to return to his regular classrooms. But I can't do that right now. But I remain hopeful we can. We cannot be guided by emotion. We need to be guided by where the facts on the ground, science, and public health take us. And that means it will not be safe to reopen our schools or start sports back up for at least another four weeks." - Governor Murphy

post_text:
April is Autism Awareness Month. The Spring Garden Community wore blue today to show their support.

Autism is a neurobiological disorder characterized by impairments in social communication and interaction as well as restricted and repetitive patterns of behavior. Individuals with autism have difficulty interacting with others: building relationships, using language, regulating their emotions, and understanding others’ points of view.

"Light It Up Blue" to show your support!

post_text:
Nutley Family Service Bureau volunteers continue to be amazing and we couldn’t be more grateful! Almost 200 households were provided with more than 400 fresh meals on Monday as part of the school breakfast and lunch program with Pomptonian. In addition, the Pantry at NFSB continues to serve our neighbors in need.

NFSB needs our help! Donations are gratefully accepted in the marked bins on the porch at the rear of the NFSB Annex 169 Chestnut Street. Next time you are shopping in person or online please consider purchasing a few extras for the Pantry such as cereal, peanut butter, canned chicken and tuna, rice, pasta, sauce, soups, and beans. Healthy snacks for children such as granola bars and raisins are also in demand. Grocery gift cards for the purchase of staples are always welcome. #NutleyStrongerTogether! #NeighborsHelpingNeighbors #AttitudeofGratitude

post_text:
Enrichment Activity Alert!

The New York Times Learning Network is running an editorial writing contest for high school students (aged 16 - 19) until mid-April. NOTE: the NYT contest is open to students as young as 10, but the younger ones can only submit entries through a teacher, so we are limiting this program to students 16 and up, who can submit on their own.

To encourage participation, Nutley Academic Booster Club will offer $15 Barnes & Noble gift cards to the first 50 eligible Nutley students ages 16 - 19 who submit an entry and also email us their proof of submission and their submitted text. Any submission that reaches the finals will receive a $50 Barnes & Noble gift card and any winners would receive a $100 Barnes & Noble gift card!

Tonight, we share an update on COVID-19 from Superintendent Glazer. Visit our website for complete letter and details.

Thank you for all of your support and patience during this unprecedented and uncertain time. While there are cases of the virus in Essex County, Nutley still does not have any confirmed cases of COVID-19 at this time. Our decision to close schools beginning Monday, March 16 is to do our part to mitigate the spread of the Coronavirus. These are not vacation days, and we will be continuing to provide daily education through the district’s Public Health Related School Closing Plan.

As we continue to follow the evolution of COVID-19, with the safety of our staff, students and community in mind, the Nutley Public Schools will close at the end of the day today, Friday, March 13. Our buildings will remain open until 6pm today for Extended Day pick-up and so that students can collect any necessary belongings. We remind all staff and students to please take their computers, chargers and any other items home.

We will continue with our plan for Monday, March 16 and we will test the technology system. Students are asked to log-into Schoology on Monday morning at 9:30 a.m. Teachers will have posted a brief discussion question for students to respond to. This will be our test.

Virtual Learning will begin for all students on Tuesday, March 17, 2020.

Read complete letter here.

post_text:
The Nutley Educational Foundation, in Partnership with the
Nutley Public School District, is Proud to Present a Screening of the New Documentary LIKE, an IndieFlix Original Documentary.

Tuesday, February 4, 6:30pm-8:30pm at NHS
🍕Make it dinner and a movie - Join us at 6pm for pizza🍕

This film is appropriate for students in grades 5-12 and ALL parents.

Technology is a tool. But… Are we addicted? How do we stop? Where do we start? The goal for this film is to inspire people of all ages, especially young adults, to self-regulate. As technology progresses and children are exposed at earlier ages, education and discussion are critical to understanding how it affects us and how we can manage it.

Click here to register:
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSejqiB1j0TRUBUjxlzi3YMeFCKny7-vk_8NZ-nm89jCDXiBTA/viewform

post_text:
Registration for the 2020 TREP$ program is open!

TREP$, short for enTREPreneur$, teaches students in grades 4-8 how to start their own businesses in 6-8 weeks. They learn the lessons in the six weekly workshops, and apply them at home as they build their business with the help of their families. The whole school community comes out to enjoy the TREP$ Marketplace where the young entrepreneurs launch their businesses together.

TREP$ sessions will be held at John H. Walker Middle school (transportation will not be provided by the district). The TREP$ program will meet at JHWMS on Wednesdays on the following dates 3/4, 3/11, 3/18, 3/25, 4/1, 5/13. The TREP$ marketplace will be held on Friday, 5/8. The cost of TREP$ will be $55. This will be open for Extended Day students, as well as non-extended day students, and will be limited to 110 students.

Click below to sign up!

The Nutley Public Schools Academic Department Coordinators, NHS Building Administrators, and School Counseling Department are presenting a scheduling program for current eighth grade parents and students on Tuesday, January 14th at 7:00 pm at Nutley High School.

During the evening, parents and students are invited to hear from each department regarding their course of study. Information will be presented that will assist students and parents in making course selections for ninth grade. There will also be an opportunity for students and parents to go on a building tour led by our NHS CORE Student Ambassadors at the conclusion of the information sessions.

post_text: Last week, NHS Spanish and Italian Honor Society students visited Yantacaw and Spring Garden schools to read to the students in both languages. "We are proud of their fluency and desire to be role models in the community by stressing the importance of bilingualism at a young age," said Coordinator of World Languages, Mrs. Julie Mitschow.
